Exercise 1

The time it takes a student to complete a TOLC-I University orientation and evaluation test follows a density function of the form

\[f(X) = \begin{cases} c(t-1)(2-t) & 1<t<2 \\ 0 & otherwise \end{cases}\]

where \(t\) is the time in hours.

  1. using the integrate() R function, determine the constant \(c\) (and verify it analytically);
one_over_c <- integrate(function(t) {(t-1)*(2-t)}, lower=1, upper=2)
one_over_c$value^(-1)
## [1] 6

Analytically,

\[ 1 = \int_{-\infty}^{\infty} f(t)\,dt = c\int_{1}^{2} (t-1)(2-t)\,dt = c \int_{1}^{2} (3t-t^2-2)\,dt = c\int_{1}^{2}\left(\frac{3}{2}t^2-\frac{t^3}{3}-2t\right)dt = \frac{c}{6} \Rightarrow c=6\] b. write the set of four R functions and plot the pdf and cdf, respectively;

pdf_f <- function(t) { func <- ifelse(t>1 & t<2, 6*(t-1)*(2-t), 0) 
  return(func)
}

cdf_f <- function(t) { func <- ifelse(t<1, 0, 
                                      ifelse(t<=2, 9*t^2 - 2*t^3 - 12*t + 5,
                                             1)) 
  return(func) 
}

# the CDF is not easily invertible, so I use the acceptance/rejection method
r_f <- function(x) {
  a <- 1
  b <- 2
  n <- 10000
  udist1 <- runif(n, a, b)
  udist2 <- runif(n, 0, 1)
  f.max <- 1.5
  y <- ifelse(udist2 * f_max < pdf_f(udist1), udist1, NA)
  y.clean <- y[!is.na(y)]
  return(y.clean[1:x])
}

q_f <- function(p) {
  cdf_values <- cdf_f(seq(1,2,0.001))
  x <- max(cdf_values[cdf_values<p])
  return(x)
}
  1. evaluate the probability that the student will finish the aptitude test in more than 75 minutes. And that it will take 90 and 120 minutes.
more75 <- 1-cdf_f(1.25) # 75 minutes = 1.25 hours
paste("The probability that the student will finish the aptitude test in more than 75 minutes is", more75)
## [1] "The probability that the student will finish the aptitude test in more than 75 minutes is 0.84375"
# my guess is that the exercise asks for the time *between* 90 and 120 minutes
betw90and120 <- cdf_f(2)-cdf_f(1.5)
paste("The probability that the student will finish the aptitude test in 90 minutes is", betw90and120)
## [1] "The probability that the student will finish the aptitude test in 90 minutes is 0.5"

Exercise 2

The lifetime of tires sold by an used tires shop is \(10^4\cdot x\) km, where \(x\) is a random variable following the distribution function

\[f(X) = \begin{cases} 2/x^2 & 1 < x < 2 \\ 0 & otherwise \end{cases}\]

  1. write the set of four R functions and plot the pdf and cdf, respectively;
pdf_f <- function(t) { func <- ifelse(t>1 & t<2, 2/(x^2), 0) 
  return(func)
}

cdf_f <- function(t) { func <- ifelse(t<1, 0, 
                                      ifelse(t<=2, 2 - 2/t,
                                             1)) 
  return(func) 
}

r_f <- function(n) {
  u1 <- runif(n, 0, 1)
  inv_cdf <- 2/(2-u1)
  return(inv_cdf[1:n])
}

q_f <- function(p) {
  cdf_values <- cdf_f(seq(1,2,0.001))
  x <- max(cdf_values[cdf_values<p])
  return(x)
}

x <- seq(1,2.5,0.001)
plot(x, pdf_f(x),
     xlab = "x",
     ylab = "PDF",
     type = "s",
     col = "blue",
     main = "PDF")

plot(x, cdf_f(x),
     xlab = "x",
     ylab = "CDF",
     type = "s",
     col = "blue",
     main = "CDF")

  1. determine the probability that tires will last less than 15000 km;
less15000 <- cdf_f(1.5)
paste("The probability that the tires will last less than 15000 km is", less15000)
## [1] "The probability that the tires will last less than 15000 km is 0.666666666666667"
  1. sample 3000 random variables from the distribution and determine the mean value and the variance, using the expression \(Var(X) = E[X^2] E[X]^2\).
samples <- r_f(3000)
m <- mean(samples)
v <- mean(samples^2)-m^2
paste("The mean is", m, "and the variance is", v)
## [1] "The mean is 1.38781478093627 and the variance is 0.0779843801847377"

Exercise 3

Markovs inequality represents an upper boud to probability distributions:

\[P(X \geq k) \leq \frac{E[X]}{k} \qquad \text{for } k>0\] having defined a function

\[G(k) = 1-F(k) \equiv P(X \geq k)\]

plot \(G(k)\) and the Markovs upper bound for:

  1. the exponential, Exp\((\lambda= 1)\), distribution function;
library(ggplot2)

G_exp <- function(x) {
  return(1-pexp(x))
}

Markov_exp <- function(x) {
  return(1/x)
}

x <- seq(0,10,0.001)

plot(x, G_exp(x), 
     type='l', 
     main="Markov's inequality for the exponential distribution Exp(lambda=1)",
     xlab="x", 
     ylab="G(x)", 
     xlim = c(0,10), 
     ylim=c(0,3), 
     col = "blue")

lines(x, Markov_exp(x), 
      col = "red")

legend("topright", 
       legend=c("Exp(lambda=1)", "Markov bound"),
       col=c("blue", "red"), 
       lty=1:2)

  1. the uniform, \(\mathcal{U}(3,5)\), distribution function;
G_unif <- function(x) {
  return(1-punif(x,3,5))
}

Markov_unif <- function(x) {

}

x <- seq(0,10,0.001)

plot(x, G_unif(x),

Exercise 4

Chebyshevs inequality tells us that

\[P\left(\left| X - \mu \right| \geq k \sigma \right) \leq \frac{1}{k^2}\] which can also be written as

\[P\left(\left| \frac{X-\mu}{\sigma}\right|<k\right) \geq 1 - \frac{1}{k^2}\] use R to show, with a plot, that Chebyshevs inequality is an upper bound to the following distributions:

  1. a normal distribution, \(N(\mu = 3, \sigma = 5)\)
chebyshev <- function(x) {
  return (1-(1/x^2))
}
# mu = 3
# sigma = 5
g <- function(x) {
  return(pnorm((5*x+3),3,5)-pnorm(3-5*x,3,5))
}

x <- seq(0,10,0.001)

plot(x, g(x), 
     type='l', 
     main="Chebyshevs inequality for the normal distribution N(mu=3, sigma=5)",
     xlab="x", 
     ylab="P", 
     xlim = c(0,5), 
     ylim=c(0,1), 
     col = "blue")

lines(x, chebyshev(x), 
      col = "red")

legend("bottomright", 
       legend=c("N(mu=3, sigma=5)", "Chebyshev bound"),
       col=c("blue", "red"), 
       lty=1:2)

  1. an exponential distribution, Exp\((\lambda = 1)\)
# mu = 1/lambda
# sigma = 1/lambda^2
e <- function(x) {
  return(pexp(1+x)-pexp(1-x))
}

x <- seq(0,10,0.001)

plot(x, e(x), 
     type='l', 
     main="Chebyshevs inequality for the exponential distribution Exp(lambda=1)",
     xlab="x", 
     ylab="P", 
     xlim = c(0,5), 
     ylim=c(0,1), 
     col = "blue")

lines(x, chebyshev(x), 
      col = "red")

legend("bottomright", 
       legend=c("Exp(lambda=1)", "Chebyshev bound"),
       col=c("blue", "red"), 
       lty=1:2)

  1. a uniform distribution \(\mathcal{U}(1 \sqrt{2}, 1 + \sqrt{2})\)
# mu = 0
# sigma = (b^2+a^2-ab)/3 = 5/3
u <- function(x) {
  return(punif(x*5/3,1-2^(1/2),1+2^(1/2))-punif(-x*5/3,1-2^(1-2),1+2^(1/2)))
}

x <- seq(0,10,0.001)

plot(x, u(x), 
     type='l', 
     main="Chebyshevs inequality for the uniform distribution U(1-sqrt(2),1+sqrt(2))",
     xlab="x", 
     ylab="P", 
     xlim = c(0,5), 
     ylim=c(0,1), 
     col = "blue")

lines(x, chebyshev(x), 
      col = "red")

legend("bottomright", 
       legend=c("U(1-sqrt(2),1+sqrt(2))", "Chebyshev bound"),
       col=c("blue", "red"), 
       lty=1:2)

  1. a Poisson, \(Pois(\lambda = 1/3)\), distribution function
# mu = 1/lambda
# sigma = 1/lambda
p <- function(x) {
  return(ppois(x*3+3,1/3)-ppois(3-x*3,1/3))
}

x <- seq(0,10,0.001)

plot(x, p(x), 
     type='l', 
     main="Chebyshevs inequality for the Poisson distribution Pois(lambda=1/3)",
     xlab="x", 
     ylab="P",

     ylim=c(0,1),

lines(x, chebyshev(x),

       legend=c("Poiss(lambda=1/3)", "Chebyshev bound"),

       lty=1:2)
